Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is overfitting?
AI Response

Overfitting occurs when a model learns training data too well—including noise—causing poor generalization
to new data. Symptoms include high train accuracy but low validation accuracy.

Example 1.2

User

What is attention mechanism?
AI Response

Attention allows a model to focus on relevant input parts during output generation. Self-attention in
transformers computes weighted relationships between all token pairs.

Example 1.3

User

What is the bias-variance tradeoff?
AI Response

High bias = underfitting (oversimplified model); high variance = overfitting (over-complex model). Good
models balance both to minimize total prediction error.

Example 1.4

User

What is the softmax function?
AI Response

Softmax converts a vector of raw scores (logits) into probabilities that sum to 1, typically used as the final
activation in multi-class classification models.

Example 1.5

User

What is feature engineering?
AI Response

Feature engineering creates or transforms input variables using domain knowledge to improve model
performance. It includes scaling, encoding, and creating interaction terms.

Example 1.6

User

What is a neural network?
AI Response

A neural network is a series of algorithms modeled after the human brain, consisting of input, hidden, and
output layers, with weights adjusted during training to minimize prediction error.

Example 1.7

User

What is batch normalization?
AI Response



Batch normalization normalizes layer inputs to have zero mean and unit variance, stabilizing training,
reducing initialization sensitivity, and acting as a mild regularizer.

Example 1.8

User

What is the ROC curve?
AI Response

The ROC curve plots true positive rate vs false positive rate at various thresholds. AUC (Area Under Curve)
summarizes performance—a perfect model has AUC = 1.0.

Example 1.9

User

What is RLHF?
AI Response

Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback trains a reward model on human preference data, then uses
RL (PPO) to fine-tune an LLM to produce outputs humans prefer.

Example 1.10

User

What is dropout?
AI Response

Dropout randomly sets a fraction of neuron activations to zero during training, preventing co-adaptation of
neurons and reducing overfitting.



